@guyzmo: could anyone explain why `)3:wq!` works but not `)3:x!`?

@gumnos: @guyzmo: The ":x" only writes if the file is considered changed. No change was made to the file, so Vim exits without actually writing it. As I mention in my 2nd comment here, to use "x!", you'd have to modify the file first (the initial "x")

@shollinshead: How does )3:wq! work when id dosn't delete anything :S?

@gumnos: @shollinshead: The difference is that ":x" only writes if the buffer has been modified; whereas ":w[q]" writes regardless of whether modifications have been made.

@martinodelilo: can somebody explains what's happening here?

@gumnos: @martinodelilo: the ")" jumps to the next sentence, starting with the "LINE1". Once there, the "3:" prepopulates the Ex command-line with ":.,+2". It then writes just those three lines to the (not-)named file, which, when the name is absent, is the same name as the current file. Finally, it quits. The "!" is there to force the overwriting of the current/existing file. The actual details are at ":help :wq" where you can read ":[range]wq[!] [++opt] [file]↵Same as above, but only write the lines in [range]."

